  <mainDescription>&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Purpose&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Issue Trends are monitored to understand the rate at which the team is finding and resolving issues. It answers the&#xD;
    following questions:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        How often is the team identifying issues?&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Is the team resolving issues as quickly as it is identifying them?&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Definition&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Monitor&amp;nbsp;issues and issues management performance by&amp;nbsp;tracking&amp;nbsp;how many issues are in each state in each&#xD;
    week/iteration.&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;br />&#xD;
    Count the number of issue in each state (e.g. submitted, assigned, resolved) and total the number of issues in each&#xD;
    week / iteration&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Analysis&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    A good way to monitor Issues Trends is with a line chart. Plot the number of issues for each state in each iteration on&#xD;
    the Y axis and iterations on the X axis.&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Expected Trend&lt;/strong> - As the project progresses, the total number of issues and the number of resolved&#xD;
    issues should increase. At the end of the project the total number of issues should equal the number of resolved&#xD;
    issues. The number of assigned issues should follow the number of submitted issues and should be zero at the end of the&#xD;
    project.&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;strong>High number of Submitted and Assigned issues remaining later in the lifecycle&lt;/strong> - This trend can&#xD;
    indicate a problem. Check individual issues and confirm that high severity issues are handled as soon as possible.&#xD;
    Otherwise, these issues will likely put the project at risk. Some issues need stakeholder negotiation and commitment.&#xD;
    In general, the team should review their project planning process to determine if process improvements are&#xD;
    necessary.&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Sudden&amp;nbsp;Jump&lt;/strong> - A jump on the&amp;nbsp;chart of Submitted issues signifies increasing project&#xD;
    difficulties. The team should look at the submitted issues and take corrective actions as appropriate. The&#xD;
    corresponding corrective actions may be observed through a follow-on rise in the same or next iteration of the assigned&#xD;
    and resolved states.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Flat -&lt;/strong> Non-zero flat lines on the chart indicate no new issue arrivals and no corrective actions. The&#xD;
    team should analyze the root cause and take the appropriate actions to drive issues to closure.&amp;nbsp; Note that&#xD;
    identifying no new issues can be a good or a bad indicator. The team may be in good shape with no new problems arising,&#xD;
    or they may not be doing a good job at identifying issues.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;br />&#xD;
    Below is an example of an Issue Trends chart.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;img alt=&quot;Issue trends report&quot; src=&quot;resources/issue_trends.gif&quot; width=&quot;600&quot; height=&quot;518&quot; />&#xD;
&lt;/p>&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Frequency and reporting&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Data is harvested for reporting purposes before the end of each iteration. The team reviews Issue Trends during their&#xD;
    iteration assessment meetings.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Collection and reporting tools&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    IBM&amp;reg; Rational&amp;reg; Quality Manager&amp;reg; and IBM&amp;reg; Rational&amp;reg; TeamConcert&amp;reg; collect Issue Trend data. IBM&amp;reg; Rational&amp;reg; Insight&amp;reg;&#xD;
    reports on this metric.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Assumptions and prerequisites&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The team has a tool in place to collect issue data, and has identified states for measurement&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Issue status updates are collected with date stamps&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Pitfalls, advice, and countermeasures&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Issues may be in some states more than once. Confirm the tool used accounts for this.&lt;br />&#xD;
        &lt;br />&#xD;
        &lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></mainDescription>
